text: SYNLETT0936-52141437-2096 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York 2017, 28, A–E letter en Preparation of 2-Substituted 3-Methoxycarbonyl-4-methoxyfu- rans that Allow Access to Highly Functionalized Naphthalenes via  Regioselective Cycloaddition with Alkoxybenzyne Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute of Technology,  2-12-1 O-okayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo 152-8551, Japan ksuzuki@chem.titech.ac.jp In connection with our ongoing study toward the total syntheses  of  tetracenomycin  C1  (1)  and  lactonamycin2  (2) (Scheme  1),  we  required  a  unified  approach  for  the  con- struction of highly functionalized naphthalene scaffold (CD rings in 1 and DE rings in 2 highlighted in blue).3 The ret- rosynthetic analysis shown in Scheme 1 suggested a poten- tial  approach  by  the  assembly  of  alkoxyfuran  I  and  α- alkoxybenzyne  II  via  [4+2]  cycloaddition,  which  seemed promising  in  light  of  three  literature  precedents  (Scheme 2). Received: 06.05.2017 Accepted after revision: 14.06.2017 Published online: 05.07.2017 DOI: 10.1055/s-0036-1590825; Art ID: st-2017-b0332-l Abstract  A  facile  synthetic  method  of  2-substituted  3-methoxycar- bonyl-4-methoxyfurans  has  been  developed,  allowing  construction  of highly functionalized naphthalene derivatives via (1) regioselective ben- zyne [4+2] cycloaddition with α-alkoxybenzyne and (2) reductive aro- matization. Key words  natural products, cycloaddition, furans, benzyne

Scheme 1   Approach to naphthalene scaffolds characteristic to 1 and 2 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–E R = α-L-rhodinosyl lactonamycin (2) (1)  Reactivity:  Although  furans  are  generally  less  reac- tive  dienes  in  Diels–Alder  reactions,  their  [4+2]  reactions with  arynes  have  been  well  documented4  thanks  to  the high reactivity of the latter species by the unusually low-ly- ing LUMO (Scheme 2, A).5 (2)  Regioselectivity:  If  one  considers  substitution  pat- terns  of  the  two  alkoxy  groups  of  two  reaction  partners  I and II (Scheme 1, highlighted in red), one could expect a fa- vorable  regioselectivity  by  the  literature  precedent6  of  β- alkoxyfuran III and α-alkoxybenzyne IV (Scheme 2, B). (3)  Ring-opening  reductive  aromatization:  Conversion of the [4+2] cycloadduct into naphthalene is supported by several literature precedents (Scheme 2, C).7 To put this plan into practice, however, two challenges were foreseen: First, since there had been no reports on fu- ran I with this particular substitution pattern, the prepara- tive method had to be developed. Second, even if I became available, complications may arise at the stage of the cyclo- addition  as  well  as  the  ring-opening  process  by  the  pres- ence of multifunctional groups on the furan ring, that may cast steric/electronic influence on the reactivity/selectivity outcomes. Scheme 2   Three precedents for furan–benzyne cycloaddition . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

In this communication, we wish to report the successful implementation of this scenario, including development of a  facile  protocol  for  preparing  trisubstituted  furans  5  and 12, and their regioselective cycloaddition reactions with α- alkoxybenzyne and subsequent reductive ring opening. Among various methods for furan syntheses, the Feist– Benary  reaction  is  useful  for  the  preparation  of  3-alkoxy- carbonylfurans  (Scheme  3,  A):8  Base-promoted  reaction  of β-ketoesters  with  α-chloroketones  provides  dihydrofuran V, and acid-catalyzed dehydration gives furan VI bearing 3- alkoxycarbonyl group. However, this protocol is not directly applicable to the synthesis of furan I, as the introduction of the C4 methoxy group is not possible. To address the issue, we came up with an idea of using furanone  VII,  which  is  readily  available  from  β-ketoesters and chloroacetyl chloride.9 If viable, this approach would al- low us to prepare various furans bearing different C2 sub- stituents (R′) by employing a suitable β-ketoester precursor. Scheme  4  shows  the  initial  feasibility  study  on  the preparation  of  furan  5.  According  to  a  literature  proce- dure,9d  methyl  acetoacetate  (3)  was  treated  with  Mg(OEt)2 (1.0 equiv) (EtOH, toluene, r.t., 1 h) to form the correspond- ing  magnesium  enolate,  which  reacted  with  chloroacetyl chloride (1.1 equiv) (MeCN, 0 °C, 1.5 h) to give furanone 4 in 27% yield. © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–E For the conversion of 4 into the desired furan 5, we ini- tially  examined  basic  conditions  to  form  the  enolate  and trapping  with  methylating  agents,  such  as  MeOTf  and Me3O+BF4 On the other hand, acidic conditions provided a promis- ing  result:  Upon  treatment  of  furanone  4  (Rf  =  0.20,  hex- ane/EtOAc  =  2:1)  with  PPTS  in  MeOH,  the  reaction  slowly proceeded (r.t., 24 h), albeit not to full conversion. The for- mation of a new compound was suggested by TLC analysis (Rf = 0.70, hexane/EtOAc = 2:1). Chromatographic purifica- tion (SiO2) gave small amount of furan 5 (9% yield) and 18% recovery of 4. After  considerable  experimentation,  the  yield  of  5  was improved  by  three  key  modifications  (Table  1):  (1)  use  of stronger  acids,  (2)  lower  concentration,  and  (3)  use  of trimethyl orthoformate as a dehydrating agent.

The  yield  of  furan  5  increased  slightly  by  using TsOH·H2O (Table 1, entry 2), and even more with TfOH (Ta- ble  1,  entry  3).  While  many  unknown  products  were  pro- duced under these conditions, a clean reaction occurred un- der more dilute conditions (0.025 M), giving 5 in 44% yield (Table 1, entry 4). However, we were not able to find suit- able conditions to complete this reaction. Eventually, how- ever, we were pleased to find that the use of trimethyl or- thoformate  (5  equiv)  allowed  full  conversion,  giving  5  in 49%  yield  (Table  1,  entry  5).  Finally,  the  optimal  yield  of  5 (87%)  was  achieved  by  using  TsOH·H2O  in  the  presence  of trimethyl orthoformate (Table 1, entry 6). The robustness of this reaction was demonstrated by conducting the reaction on a 9.0 g scale, giving 5 in 82% yield (Table 1, entry 7). It turned out that furan 5, once obtained as hygroscopic white  solid,  was  stable  enough  to  be  stored  in  a  tightly sealed  container  over  one  week  (r.t.).  A  precaution  is  the tight sealing, in that storage in an open vial (r.t., 12 h) led to decomposition, giving a yellow sticky oil (Figure 1).

Experimental  procedure  for  synthesis  of  furan  5  is  as follows:  To  a  mixture  of  furanone  4  (200  mg,  1.28  mmol) and trimethyl orthoformate (0.70 mL, 6.4 mmol) in MeOH (51  mL)  was  added  TsOH·H2O  (121  mg,  0.636  mmol)  at room temperature. After stirring for 22 hours at room tem- perature,  the  reaction  was  quenched  by  adding  Et3N  (0.5 mL). The resulting mixture was poured into saturated aque- ous  NaHCO3,  and  the  products  were  extracted  with  EtOAc (4×).  The  combined  organic  extracts  were  dried  (Na2SO4) and  concentrated  in  vacuo.  The  residue  was  purified  by flash  column  chromatography  (silica  gel,  hexane,  EtOAc  = 4:1) to afford furan 510 (189 mg, 87% yield) as a white solid. With  the  requisite  furan  5  in  hand,  the  utility  in  the [4+2] cycloaddition was examined by the reaction with the α-alkoxybenzyne  species,  generated  from  o-iodoaryl  tri- flate 6 (Scheme 5): Upon treatment of a mixture of furan 5 (1.4 equiv) and o-iodoaryl triflate 6 in THF with n-BuLi (1.2 equiv,  –95  °C,  20  min),11  the  cycloaddition  smoothly  pro- ceeded  in  a  regioselective  manner  to  give  the  desired  cy- cloadduct 7 in 80% yield and a small amount of regioisomer 8 (5% yield). Structures of cycloadducts 7 and 8 were con- firmed by HMBC experiments (Scheme 5, A). Figure 1   Property of furan 5
Scheme 5   Regioselective [4+2] benzyne cycloaddition to furan 5 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–E

This highly regioselective cycloaddition could be inter- preted as follows (Figure 2). The starting point of discussion is the long-known12 and well-exploited13 polarization of α- alkoxybenzyne  IX  in  that  a  higher  electrophilicity  is  dis- played at the carbon distal from the α-alkoxy group (Figure 2, A).13c,f,g,i,14 Given the case, a prototype of the present case is  Sargent’s  report  on  the  reaction  of  α-methoxybenzyne (X)  with  β-methoxyfuran  (XI),  where  the  cycloaddition mode shown in Figure 2 (B) is favored (selectivity 86:14).6 Considering the polarization of furan XI by electron dona- tion from the methoxy group, this outcome could be ratio- nalized by the HOMO–LUMO interaction as shown in Figure 2 (B). Turning attention to the present case, furan 5 could be regarded  as  a  derivative  of  β-methoxyfuran  (XI)  with  two extra  groups,  that  is,  2-methyl  and  3-methoxycarbonyl groups (Figure 2, C). Prior to the experiment, we wondered how these extra groups affect the reactivity and the regio- selectivity  of  furan  5.  A  DFT  calculation  showed  that  the HOMO of 5 also has the largest coefficient at C5 (Figure 2, C, right),15  suggesting  the  preferred  mode  of  cycloaddition  A (Figure  2,  D)  from  the  view  of  the  frontier  orbital  interac- tion. Despite the methyl group would discourage the mode A  by  the  steric  effect,  the  observed  high  regioselectivity suggests how decisive the orbital interaction is, overriding the steric effect.

Scheme 6 shows the further conversion of cycloadduct 7 for the model construction of the CD rings in tetracenomy- cin C (1), which was realized by reductive aromatization by exploiting  a  low-valent  titanium  species  as  a  reductant:7a Upon treatment of 7 with TiCl4 (5 equiv) and Zn (10 equiv) in  THF  (0  °C,  1  h),  the  reaction  proceeded  nicely  to  give naphthalene 9 in 71% yield. Having established this protocol, we became interested in  the  application  to  the  construction  of  the  DEF  rings  of lactonamycin  (2,  Scheme  7).  By  setting  the  pyrrolidone- fused naphthalene 15 as the target, the model study started Figure 2   Rationale for the regioselectivity . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C with β-ketoester 1016 having a γ-amino group. In the reac- tion  of  10  with  chloroacetyl  chloride,  choice  of  the  base proved  decisive:  The  initial  attempt  using  Mg(OEt)2  (vide supra) resulted in no reaction. After screening various bas- es, the use of NaH (1.0 equiv, CH2Cl2, r.t., 0.5 h) proved effec- tive,  giving  furanone  11  in  31%  yield.17  The  next  step  was the acid-mediated formation of the furan: Treatment of 11 with  TsOH·H2O  (0.5  equiv)  and  trimethyl  orthoformate  (5 equiv,  0.025  M  in  MeOH,  r.t.,  72  h)  gave  furan  12  in  86% yield. Notably, the reaction proceeded without touching the N-Boc group.

Furthermore,  the  benzyne  [4+2]  cycloaddition  of  12 with  α-alkoxybenzyne  proceeded  in  a  regioselective  man- ner,  giving  the  cycloadduct  13  in  71%  yield  and  a  trace Scheme 6   Reductive aromatization Scheme 7   Construction of the DEF-ring system of lactonamycin R = α-L-rhodinosyl lactonamycin (2) TiCl4 (5 equiv) Zn (10 equiv) n-BuLi THF, –95 °C 25 min © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–E amount of its regioisomer. Due to the line broadening of the 1H  NMR  spectra,  the  structure  assignment  of  the  cycload- duct 13 was not possible at this stage. However, it was as- signed as such by the successful conversion into the target- ed  pyrrolidone  15  as  described  in  the  following.  After  re- ductive  aromatization  (TiCl4,  Zn,  THF,  r.t.,  8  h),  acid- mediated detachment of the N-Boc group (TFA, CH2Cl2, r.t., 1 h) triggered the lactamization3d to afford 15 in 89% yield. The  structure  of  15  was  unambiguously  confirmed  by HMBC experiments (Scheme 7, A). In retrospect, the high regioselectivity of the cycloaddi- tion of furan  12 is notable: In spite of the increased steric demand around the C2 position by the presence of an ami- nomethyl  group,  the  selectivity  was  even  better  than  that observed in the reaction of furan 5 (cf. Scheme 5).

In summary, we have developed a viable method to pre- pare  2-substituted  3-methoxycarbonyl-4-methoxyfurans, which  allowed  the  construction  of  highly  functionalized naphthalene  derivatives  via  (1)  regioselective  benzyne [4+2]  cycloaddition  with  α-alkoxybenzyne  and  (2)  reduc- tive aromatization. Further works on the application to nat- ural product synthesis are under way in our laboratory.
